cultivarNotes:
Cross-pollination between two or more different cultivars is strongly recommended — stagger bloom times slightly for reliability but ensure overlap. Cultivar selection varies meaningfully by region: northern highbush cultivars (the standard V. corymbosum selections) are best suited to Zones 4–7; southern gardeners in Zones 7–9 should instead seek southern highbush cultivars (hybrids of V. corymbosum × V. darrowii) such as 'O'Neal', 'Emerald', 'Star', and 'Jewel', which require far fewer chill hours; Pacific NW gardeners have a different cultivar landscape and should consult regional extension resources. For northern growers in Zones 4–7, the following are the most reliable standard selections:
**'Bluecrop'** (mid-season; the benchmark standard cultivar for the Northeast; reliable, productive, excellent flavor, light blue medium-large berry; widely available at every nursery; plant this as the anchor of any blueberry planting; MBG lists this cultivar with a dedicated page);
**'Blueray'** (early to mid-season; large berry; considered by many to have exceptional flavor — among the best-tasting highbush cultivars; excellent cross-pollinator for 'Bluecrop'; ornamentally attractive fall color);
**'Jersey'** (late-season; classic heritage cultivar first released in 1928; extends the harvest into August; medium berry with good flavor; vigorous upright grower to 6–8'; pairs well with 'Bluecrop' for cross-pollination);
**'Patriot'** (early season; Zone 3–7; compact habit; excellent cold-hardiness; one of the most reliable performers for challenging or exposed sites; good flavor; recommended for difficult or marginal sites);
**'Northblue'** (half-high type, 2–3' tall; a cross between highbush and lowbush species; extremely cold-hardy Zone 3; very ornamental — brilliant red fall color, compact form; excellent for the front of a planting or ornamental use in a visible bed; produces well despite compact size; smaller berry than standard highbush but excellent flavor).
